The paper proposes a method for weakly supervised object localization using adversarial learning. This involves training a network to dynamically localize discriminative object regions during the forward pass, and then erasing these regions to force the network to discover new and complementary object regions. The paper focuses on computer vision tasks, specifically object localization, which suggests that it is most likely to belong to the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves training a neural network, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. The paper also involves mathematical proofs, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves experiments with image datasets, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.MM (Multimedia) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-categories.
